\section*{3.2 Approximation and Approximation Errors in Real-World Contexts}

\subsection*{Key ideas}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Approximation} is the process of rounding off a given number to give an approximate value.
\item In real life, we do not always round off using the usual rules. We choose a type of rounding that makes sense for the situation.
\item Rounding off non-exact values in intermediate working can cause follow-through errors.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{A. Different types of rounding in real life}

\textbf{1) When you must round up (to make sure you have enough)}\\
\textbf{Example: buses}\\
215 students and 5 teachers are going by bus.
\begin{align*}
\text{Total people} &= 215 + 5 = 220,\\
\text{Buses needed} &= 220 \div 30 \approx 7.33.
\end{align*}
You need \textbf{8 buses}.

\medskip
\textbf{2) When you may round down (because of a rule or policy)}\\
\textbf{Example: paying cash and rounding down to the nearest 5 cents}\\
Grocery bill $= \$48.19$. Nearest 5-cent amounts are $\$48.15$ and $\$48.20$.\\
Round down $\Rightarrow$ pay $\$48.15$.

\medskip
\textbf{3) When you round down for safety}\\
\textbf{Example: maximum load}\\
A lift carries a maximum load of 897 kg. You must display the maximum load correct to the nearest 100 kg.\\
Showing 900 kg may allow overloading, so show \textbf{800 kg}.

\subsection*{B. Rounding errors and follow-through errors}

\textbf{1) Follow-through error}\\
A follow-through error can occur if non-exact values in intermediate working are not rounded off to a sufficient degree of accuracy.

\medskip
\textbf{2) Why totals can look ``wrong'' after rounding}\\
If individual percentages are rounded, the total may become $99.9\%$ or $100.1\%$ instead of exactly $100\%$.
\[
62.3\% + 17.3\% + 20.3\% = 99.9\%.
\]
In practice, the total is often written as $100\%$ to avoid confusion.

\medskip
\textbf{3) How to reduce follow-through errors}
\begin{itemize}
\item If the final answer is required to be accurate to 3 significant figures, intermediate non-exact values should usually be given to at least 4 significant figures (often 4 or 5 significant figures).
\item Use the values stored in the calculator to compute the next step of the working.
\end{itemize}

\medskip
\textbf{4) Example showing follow-through error}\\
Area of a square $= 131\text{ cm}^2$.
\[
\text{Length}=\sqrt{131}\approx 11.4\text{ cm (to 3 s.f.)}
\]
\textbf{Perimeter (wrong approach):}
\[
11.4 \times 4 = 45.6
\]
\textbf{Perimeter (better approach):} use a more accurate intermediate value, e.g.\ $11.446$:
\[
11.446 \times 4 = 45.784 \approx 45.8\text{ cm (to 3 s.f.)}
\]

\subsection*{C. Approximate value vs value with specified degree of accuracy}

\textbf{1) ``Equal to \dots\ (to \dots)'' is different from ``approximately \dots''}\\
``Population is approximately $500\,000$'' is an estimate without a clear degree of accuracy.\\
``Population is $500\,000$ (to 1 s.f.)'' has a specified degree of accuracy.

\medskip
\textbf{Checking exact values}
\begin{itemize}
\item $450\,000$ rounded to 1 s.f.\ is $500\,000$, so it \textbf{can} be equal to $500\,000$ (to 1 s.f.).
\item $449\,999$ rounded to 1 s.f.\ is $400\,000$, so it \textbf{cannot} be equal to $500\,000$ (to 1 s.f.).
\end{itemize}
But $449\,999$ can still be described as \textbf{approximately $500\,000$} (about half a million).

\medskip
\textbf{2) Using $\approx$ and giving degree of accuracy}
\begin{itemize}
\item Avoid writing $\sqrt{131}\text{ cm} \approx 11.4\text{ cm}$ without stating accuracy.
\item Write: $\sqrt{131}\text{ cm} = 11.4\text{ cm (to 3 s.f.)}$.
\item Use $\approx$ when estimating an unknown quantity in real life and the degree of accuracy is not important, e.g.\ distance $\approx 10$ km.
\end{itemize}

\medskip
\textbf{3) Measurements and ``approximately''}\\
With a ruler, we can only measure up to half the smallest marking.\\
If a length is recorded as $2.75$ cm, it may be accurate to $\pm 0.05$ cm.\\
Saying ``approximately $2.75$ cm'' does not clearly state the degree of accuracy.

\subsection*{Simple example problems (with worked solutions)}

\textbf{1) Buses}\\
A group has 182 students and 6 teachers. Each bus carries 30 passengers. How many buses are required?
\[
\text{Total}=182+6=188,\qquad 188\div 30 \approx 6.27
\]
So \textbf{7 buses} are required.

\medskip
\textbf{2) Cash payment (rounding down to nearest 5 cents)}\\
A bill is $\$23.44$. The shop rounds down to the nearest 5 cents. How much do you pay?\\
Nearest 5-cent amounts: $\$23.40,\ \ \$23.45$. Round down $\Rightarrow \ \$23.40$.

\medskip
\textbf{3) Maximum load}\\
A machine can take a maximum load of 742 kg. You must display the maximum load correct to the nearest 100 kg. What should be shown?\\
Show \textbf{700 kg} (round down for safety).

\medskip
\textbf{4) Approximate vs specified degree of accuracy}\\
Can $349\,999$ be equal to $400\,000$ (to 1 s.f.)?\\
To 1 s.f.\ we round to the nearest $100\,000$. $349\,999$ rounds to $300\,000$.\\
So \textbf{No}.

