\section*{3.3 Estimation and Estimation Errors in Real-World Contexts}

\subsection*{Key ideas}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Estimation} is the process of guessing the value of an unknown quantity in real life.
\item Estimation often uses approximate values to make mental calculation easier.
\item Estimation helps you check whether an answer is reasonable or obviously wrong.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{A. Estimation of computations}

\textbf{How to estimate a computation}
\begin{enumerate}
\item Replace each number with an approximate value that is easy to work with.
\item Do the calculation mentally.
\item Compare with the calculator answer.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Example}\\
Check whether $392.7$ is reasonable for $31.5 + 9.87 - 2.1$.
\[
31.5 + 9.87 - 2.1 \approx 32 + 10 - 2 = 40
\]
Since $392.7$ is far from $40$, it is \textbf{not reasonable}.

\subsection*{B. Shopping with a different currency (currency conversion)}

\textbf{Main idea:} Choose an approximate conversion that is easy to remember, then break the amount into parts.

\textbf{Example}\\
Conversion rate: $1$ baht $=\text{S\$}0.039200$. Use $100$ baht $\approx \text{S\$}4$.\\
Wallet costs $225$ baht.
\[
200\text{ baht}\approx \text{S\$}8,\qquad 25\text{ baht}\approx \text{S\$}1
\]
\[
225\text{ baht}=200+25 \approx 8+1 = \text{S\$}9
\]

\subsection*{C. Value for money}

To decide which option gives better value for money, compare the costs for an equal amount.

\textbf{Important point:} Estimation can overestimate or underestimate. If two estimated values are very close, use a more careful method of estimation or use the actual values.

\textbf{Example idea}\\
Option A: 200 g costs \$7.80 \\
Option B: 250 g costs \$9.95

Estimate the cost of 250 g for Option A:
\[
250\text{ g}=200\text{ g}+50\text{ g}\approx 7.80 + 2 = 9.80
\]
Since $9.80 < 9.95$, \textbf{Option A} gives the better value for money.

\subsection*{D. Estimation of larger quantity using smaller quantity}

\textbf{Strategy:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Count how many items fit in a smaller container (or a small part).
\item Estimate how many such containers (or parts) fit in the large container (or whole).
\item Multiply.
\item Repeat a few times and take the average if needed.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{E. Estimation of area}

To estimate the area of a shaded region, divide it into parts that are approximately equal to the unshaded region.

\textbf{Example idea: ratio of areas}\\
If the shaded region can be divided into about 3 parts, each approximately the same area as the unshaded region, then
\[
\text{ratio of area of shaded region to that of unshaded region} \approx 3:1.
\]

\subsection*{Simple example problems (with worked solutions)}

\textbf{1) Reasonableness of a calculator answer}\\
A calculator shows $15\,561$ for $798 \times 195$. Is it reasonable?
\[
798 \times 195 \approx 800 \times 200 = 160\,000
\]
$15\,561$ is far from $160\,000$, so it is \textbf{not reasonable}.

\medskip
\textbf{2) Estimating a division}\\
A calculator shows $70.3$ for $218 \div 31$. Is it reasonable?
\[
218 \div 31 \approx 210 \div 30 = 7
\]
So $70.3$ is \textbf{obviously wrong}.

\medskip
\textbf{3) Currency conversion estimate}\\
A bag costs RM25. Use $\text{RM}1 \approx \text{S\$}0.30$. Estimate the price in S\$.
\[
25 \times 0.30 = 7.5
\]
So the price $\approx \text{S\$}7.50$.

\medskip
\textbf{4) Value for money}\\
Option A: 300 ml costs \$8.80\\
Option B: 350 ml costs \$10.40\\
Estimate the cost of 350 ml for Option A and decide which is better value for money.

A quick estimate: $300$ ml $\approx \$9$. Then $100$ ml $\approx \$3$, so $50$ ml $\approx \$1.50$.
\[
350\text{ ml for Option A} \approx 9 + 1.5 = \$10.5
\]
Compare: $\$10.40 < \$10.5$. So \textbf{Option B} seems to give the better value for money (the values are close).

\medskip
\textbf{5) Using a smaller quantity to estimate a larger quantity}\\
A small box holds about 40 coins. A tank holds about 60 such boxes (by size). Estimate the number of coins in the tank, and the amount of money if each coin is 10\textcent.

\[
\text{Number of coins} \approx 40 \times 60 = 2400
\]
\[
\text{Amount of money} \approx 2400 \times 10\text{¢} = 24\,000\text{¢} = \$240
\]

\end{document}
